questionRound.0.question.9.answer: Prisoner Theory in order to choose my opponents route of highest pay off and then choose my answer of highest pay off based on their choice.

1. Figure out the color that has dominant strategy. (whatever the other color chooses  this color will always make more money) |  | 2. Use the dominant strategy choice and apply to other metrics  see which is the best interest to other party | 3. Deduce other party's choice than select the best strategy for myself.

I always selected the highest possible option. When that didn't earn me the highest earnings  I would select the lower number in the next round. When that didn't work either  I kept selecting the highest number and stopped trying to predict the other player's actions.

When one row has both numbers more than the largest of the other row  I will not consider another's strategy. However  If that is not the case  I will track to the person my payoff is dependent upon and apply the same rule to figure out there choice. If they are in the same strategy  I will track to the person they are dependent on and predict what they think the other person will choose based on the same rules  except they won't trace it onward.

The rightmost box consistently had one row that had higher totals than the other  no matter what column was chosen. Thus  you could almost always predict which row that person was choosing. Assuming the person to their left was looking at this person's rows  they would guess which of their columns would be chosen  and choose a row of their own that would give them the highest total. It would proceed leftward like this. This strategy almost always worked when I was the second from the right  or even third from the right. It usually didn't work when I was the leftmose person  in a game of four. Someone  usually the third person to go (the person to my right) would mess it up by presumably looking for the box with the highest total  choosing that row and hoping for the best. This strategy would end up losing both of us tokens.

I tried not to over analyze each match  because it is impossible for me to know the precise strategies of each participant. However  before making each decision  I weighed the marginal costs of choosing each row. I figured that a good choice for one person would inevitably screw another person over. I tried to keep that in mind. After each round  I also looked to see what each person ended up choosing  in order to discern some kind of pattern in strategy. I kind of felt that at a certain point it was futile to carefully strategize  so for some rounds I would choose almost randomly.

I realized that for many of the situations  there would be a person who had the two highest earning choices on the same entry  so their choice was obvious. Assuming that each person assumed that the person above them would chose the choice that earned them the most  I would then chose the choice that earned me the most. Of course  if I was the person whose choices were obvious  I didn't have to look at anyone else's options  but simply chose the one that earned me the most and left the rest up to the decisions of the other players.

I chose whichever option paid me the most  while at the same time corresponded with whatever option I thought my opponent would choose; thus giving me a more consistently predictable payout. However  I didn't figure this strategy out until about halfway through.

I looked for the player who had an easy decision (one of his choices would definitely result in a higher payoff). Then I looked at the player whose decision depended on the first player's decision  and guess which choice player two would choose based on player one's choice. I continued this process until the player whose decision depended on the previous one I had analyzed was me  and made my decision based on what I guess the previous player would do.

It seemed that there was always one role that had an easy choice. By an easy choice  I mean both payouts for choosing X were higher than both payouts for choosing Y  or vice versa. By find the role that had the easy choice  I could work backward to figure out what choice each other role would choose based on the first role's choice for their best payout. I would do this until it got back to my role and I had discovered what would be the smartest choice of the other role and make my choice on the highest payout factoring in that other choice.

Look at all the cells and judge which choices will other participators choose and then make my own choice. In case that  there must be one participator's choices showing one choice is always better than the other one  so there should be a relatively better choice for all the participators as a whole group in the match.

The player on the right has an easy choice  because one of the rows is guaranteed to give a higher number of tokens than the other. Assuming that this player will choose the row that allows him/her to gain the most profit  you can trace back what decisions the rest of the players will make (assuming that they too understand the strategy and will want to profit as much as possible)  and then you can choose the row that allows you to profit the most. So in Display 3  Green will choose Xg because either number is higher than either number in Yg. If Blue realizes Green will make this choice  Blue will choose Yb (since 20 > 12)  and Red will choose Xr  so I (Orange) should choose Xo.
